				<td colspan="2"><span>The lack of variation shows in many aspects of the game play.  This is both good and bad.  The upside is that you dont have to worry about being excluded because you are a bard and they already have one - I cant speak for higher levels but at lower levels &lt; 30 most classes are exchangeable once you have your 4 basic classes covered.  The downside is that there is no variation in game play - you play a mage exactly like you would play a scout (ive only played these two chars up near 20).  I just read a rousing discussion on the general forum here about which classes and group make up would you want in a 24 person raid.  That kind diversity doesnt happen in EQ2.  This is not a rant on how bad EQ2 is - I like the game overall - but it isnt perfect.
<br />

<br />
Tin.</span></td>
