			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: ??? EQ2 ???<a name="71950"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 7 05 6:01 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>i actually agree quite a bit tinu...
<br />

<br />
i chose the bard in eq1 for its flexibility and wasn't disappointed.
<br />

<br />
i chose the bard in eq2 for the same reasons.  however, i was disappointed.  my disappointment doesn't stem from the fact that bards don't have flexibility in eq2 because they do.  both dirges and troubs can do many useful things in a group.
<br />

<br />
i am disappointed because i feel quite a bit of flexibility has actually been taken out of the game.  most encounters feel the same.  i think quite a bit of the skill level and subtlety has been removed from gameplay (especialy in pulling).
<br />

<br />
players can do quite a bit in eq2 and playing their character is very dynamic - linking skills, using abilities, and coordinating with your group.  but after a while it seems as if i am doing the same encounter over and over again.  instead of seeing variation in game content, all i have to play with are variations in group dynamics.  when you play with the same group and develop efficient combat strategies more variation disappears....
<br />

<br />
eq1 had its problems - camps, limited spawns, nerfs, poorly designed quests, inequity in soloing ability - but there was excitement in exploring an unkown world and the game mechanics were flexible enough to allow a wide range of interaction with the game.
<br />

<br />
eq2 has dealt with quite a few of the problems from eq1, but has introduced an entirely new set - most encounters seem like zergs, character skill is partially replaced by class uniformity, reduced xp for soloers (and making it harder and harder on duoers to group against tougher group mobs and no instancing for duos) leading to forced grouping, cookie cutter questing (at low levels), least favorite of all though are the time sinks which remain the same across both games - tradeskilling is cumbersome and often bugged.  
<br />

<br />
i can't tell you how excited i was to learn i would be able to make by own instruments in eq2 only to find out they can't yet be equipped and no one knows if they will actually modify songs' effectiveness.  i see many problems and few answers and fixes from the devs, just like eq1.
<br />

<br />
sorry to turn this into a rant, i won't go on anymore as i have always loved this board, my bard, and don't want to pollute it with more negativity.  </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
