			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: ??? EQ2 ???<a name="72534"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 26 05 3:20 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I tend to agree here. In pick up groups-- that is where you see the zerging. There its a matter of get in with what you got on hand and whale away on it till its dead, hoping everyone lives. Healers could be druids, shamans or clerics and their various sub-types. DPS generally would be sorcerer and summoner types, and the aggro holders would be warrior, brawler types. Rogues and Bards fall in there between buffers and dps, being capable of some of both. One thing they cant do is hold aggro as they have no taunt.
<br />

<br />
However, in more planned groups, there is a definite divergence of ability. With the addition of HO's, a duo has a good chance of becoming a very efficient and coordinated team, capable of taking on groups of mobs. The two duo's that I play are a Summoner / Mystic and a Warrior / Druid. I throw my bard in there whenever I can, but found that Im not as good at soloing as I was in EQ1, nor am I as efficient as a healer / buffer, but better at melee than EQ1. However, I think a LOT of that is gear--both armor (resists) and weapons (delay and damage), AND even more crucial-- upgrading all spells/ abilities to the highest available-- either App4 or Adept3.
<br />

<br />
Yes, this is a new game. That's what grabbed me and held my interest in EQ2. Yes, the landscape is changed. Little is recognizable from the old Norrath we all knew and loved. But to try to equate this game in the same way we equated EQ1 in terms of mobs, damage, groups and strategy just doesn't work.
<br />

<br />
Crafting has also come to play a huge part in this new game. Crafting has become as much fun as running around killing stuff. It's just as challenging, with spells to cast. I found that my leveling time was shared with my crafting time, slowing down the experiencing while I got my Bard to lvl 22 Jewleler and my Mystic to lvl 24 Carpenter.
<br />

<br />
All in all Ive been satisfied. Yes, there are things I miss from EQ1, but there are things I miss from Horizons as well. Yes, its not the same as WoW, but I like the looks of the landscape and the characters ever so much better here in Norrath. Just watching the sunrise or the elephants drinking from the river or the farmer herding the cows.. all that makes this game richly textured and complicated.
<br />

<br />
Glad we have our own little spot to post -- thanks Kocho<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
Dovewing
<br />
(Sonnatta FV)</span></td>
